Here is a detailed patent specification for an innovative and new way to issue collective tax certificates and other relevant permissions and approvals as digital certificates that are not transparent by using verifiable identity information, a digital ledger on a blockchain as a payment solution and machine learning. Include detailed requirements, system architecture and algorithms.

Abstract
The invention relates to a system and method for issuing digital certificates for collective taxes and other relevant approvals in a secure manner that does not allow viewing of the contents of the certificates. The system includes a blockchain-based digital ledger that stores the verifiable identity information of each user. The issuance of digital certificates is automated using machine learning algorithms that consider the user's verifiable identity information, their history of compliance with collective taxes and other relevant requirements, and their willingness to pay the associated fees. The digital certificates are non-transparent, meaning that they do not reveal the content of the collective taxes or other relevant approvals they represent. The system also includes a payment solution based on blockchain technology that allows for instantaneous and secure payments by users to the relevant authorities.

Background
Collective taxes are an important source of revenue for many governments around the world. They represent a significant portion of public spending in most countries. However, compliance with collective taxes has been an ongoing challenge for many governments, with low levels of voluntary compliance and high levels of non-compliance by certain segments of society. This has led to increased pressure on government agencies to find more efficient ways to collect these taxes and ensure compliance.

One way to improve compliance with collective taxes is through the use of digital certificates. These are digital documents that represent certain approvals or permissions, such as a certificate of collective tax compliance or an approval for access to certain services or facilities. Digital certificates can be issued in a secure manner that does not allow viewing of their content by users or authorities, ensuring privacy and confidentiality. They can also be used as a payment solution, allowing for instantaneous and secure payments by users to the relevant authorities.

Objectives
The objectives of this invention are to provide a system and method for issuing digital certificates for collective taxes and other relevant approvals in a secure manner that does not allow viewing of their content by users or authorities; to automate the issuance process using machine learning algorithms; to use blockchain technology as the underlying payment solution; and to improve compliance with collective taxes by increasing levels of voluntary compliance and reducing levels of non-compliance by certain segments of society.

System Description
The system includes:
• A blockchain-based digital ledger that stores the verifiable identity information of each user;
• Machine learning algorithms that consider the user's verifiable identity information, their history of compliance with collective taxes and other relevant requirements, and their willingness to pay the associated fees;
• A mechanism for automatically issuing digital certificates based on these factors;
• A payment solution based on blockchain technology that allows for instantaneous and secure payments by users to the relevant authorities;
• A user interface that allows users to manage their digital certificates, including viewing their status and making payments;
• A reporting module that provides real-time information about the status of collective taxes and other relevant approvals;
• A user verification module that ensures that only authorized users can access the system;
• A user authentication module that allows users to verify their identity before accessing the system;
• A data privacy module that ensures that all user data is kept securely encrypted throughout its lifecycle within the system;
• An audit trail module that records all actions taken within the system, including user activities related to issuance or renewal of digital certificates; 
And other related components as needed or desired according to implementation requirements or constraints imposed by technological limitations or constraints imposed by applicable law(s).

